public int compress(char[] chars) {
    if (chars.length == 0) return 0;
    int writeIndex = 1;
    int readIndex = 0;
    while (readIndex < chars.length) {
        int count = 1;
        while (readIndex + 1 < chars.length && chars[readIndex] == chars[readIndex + 1]) {
            readIndex++;
            count++;
        }
        chars[writeIndex++] = chars[readIndex];
        if (count > 1) {
            String countStr = Integer.toString(count);
            for (char c : countStr.toCharArray()) {
                chars[writeIndex++] = c;
            }
        }
        readIndex++;
    }
    return writeIndex;
}
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: This solution uses a two-pointer approach to iterate through the input array. It keeps track of the write index to store the compressed string and the read index to iterate through the input array. The time complexity is O(n) because each character is visited at most twice. The space complexity is O(1) because it uses a constant amount of extra space to store the write index and the count of consecutive repeating characters.

